@Jack McCullough

Change buys nothing on its own, really, so carrying it without banknotes on top would make little sense - and banknotes deserve a wallet, don't they? All the wallets I've ever had always featured a change pocket, ditto my father's. Poland suffered from inflation in the early 1990s and coins all but disappeared from circulation, as their value was essentially zero. That all changed in 1995 - inflation was brought under control, and the currency was denominated: four zeros were cut off, and thus the old 10 000 złoty became the new 1 złoty (these days roughly equivalent to your quarter), and coins were reintroduced, up to 5 złoty. But even in those few years of lack of circulation of coins wallets typically retained coin pockets, as I remember it.

These days I pay almost everywhere with my phone, anyway.

@Andrzej

Think 'coins' when people mention 'change' in regard to money. There are coin purses available, but most men in the US don't use them, they just slip the coins into a front pants pocket until they either use or store them for later redemption, hence the term "pocket change".

Of course, with the extensive use of credit and debit cards these days and tap-to-pay, one pays the entire amount and gets no cash or coins returned. I rarely see coins these days, and I've carried cash in my wallet for months without using it.

